Verify that all instances of sensitive data are cleared. Ensure that all the memory locations where sensitive data has been stored are cleared or overwritten after their use. Setting a pointer to NULL does not clear or overwrite the memory - a new value must be assigned to it. For a character array, setting each char to a new value, such as a space or a zero, will overwrite the value stored in memory. Example of improper removal of sensitive data:
            char[] ssn = getSocialSecurity();...//insufficient for removing sensitive data from memoryssn = null;
            Example of proper removal of sensitive data:
            char[] ssn = getSocialSecurity();...//proper clearing of character array to remove sensitive data from memoryfor(int i=0; i{      ssn[i] = ' ';}ssn = null;
